{"cursor":"2673","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"A 'rare species' is a group of organisms that are very uncommon or scarce. This\ndesignation may be applied to either a plant or animal taxon, and may be\ndistinct from the term [[endangered species|endangered]] or [[threatened\nspecies]]. Designation of a rare species may be made by an official body, such\nas a national government, state, or province. However, the term more commonly\nappears without reference to specific criteria. The IUCN does not normally make\nsuch designations, but may use the term in scientific\ndiscussion. [http://www.iucnredlist.org/info/categories_criteria2001\nCategories & Criteria (version 3.1) IUCN, 2001.]\n\nRarity rests on a specific species being represented by a small number of\norganisms worldwide, usually fewer than 10,000. However, a species having a very\nnarrow endemic range or fragmented habitat also influences the\nconcept. R.MacNally and G.W.Brown, [[Reptile]]s and Habitat Fragmentation in\nthe Box-ironbush Forests of Central Victoria, [[Australia]]: Predicting\nCompositional Change and Faunal Nested-ness, Oecologia 128:116-125 (2001)\nRare species are not uncommon, since nearly 75% of known species are\nrare. Dinerstein, Eric (2013) [http://books.google.co.nz/books?id=ZLkpLgEAC-\nAAJ&dq=%22The+Kingdom+of+Rarities%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nZyWUYuwM8uWiQe184GIDg&ved=0-\nCC8Q6AEwAA The Kingdom of Rarities] Island Press. ISBN 9781610911955.\n\nA species may be endangered or vulnerable, but not considered rare ifâfor\nexampleâit has a large, dispersed population, but its numbers are declining\nrapidly or predicted to do so. Rare species are generally considered threatened\nbecause a small population size is more likely to not recover from stochastic\nevents (things that could happen).\n","linknr":173,"url":"Rare_species","recorded":1376422241,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Rare_species&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Rare_species&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/fav